influenced by Latin <i>salvus</i> ‘whole’, i.e. natural). This surname is also found in England.","History: Jean Sauvage from Plouëc-du-Trieux in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany (France), married Marguerite Martin in Les Cèdres, QC, in 1782."]},{"name":"Salvage","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Monique.","English (Sussex): variant of   Savage  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Ramage","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin); French: nickname for a savage or unpredictable individual, from Old French <i>ramage</i> ‘wild, untamed’. The word is recorded once in Middle English with the sense ‘courageous’ and in Scots (spelled <i>rammage</i>) as ‘rash, furious’. Compare   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Sabin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Northamptonshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Sabin</i> (from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>; see 2 below) or its female equivalent <i>Sabine</i> (from Latin <i>Sabina</i>). In medieval England the feminine form was always more popular as a personal name.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Sabin</i>, from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>. The name was originally referred to the Sabines, an ancient Italic people of central Italy whose name is of uncertain origin. In the 8th century  BC  the Romans slaughtered the Sabine menfolk and carried off the women. More influential as far as name-giving is concerned was the existence of several early Christian saints named <i>Sabinus</i>.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sabháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sabhán</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sabh</i> ‘cub’. As an Irish surname, this has mostly been absorbed into   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Selvidge","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","from Middle English <i>selvage</i>, <i>silvadge</i> ‘edge of a cloth, bandage, ornamental edging (to a cloth or garment)’, hence a nickname for someone who made or sold such items.","variant of   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Savidge","meanings":["English: variant of   Savage  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":9,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Savage IV was born on 24 May 1280, in Derbyshire, England, his father, John Savage, was 30 and his mother, Abigail Stanton, was 18. He had at least 1 son. He died about November 1311, in his hometown, at the age of 31."},"et":{"24 May 1280–about November 1311":"24. mai 1280–umbes november 1311","1270–1331":"1270–1331","1280–1311":"1280–1311","1285–1331":"1285–1331","1311–Male":"1311–Surnud","1250–1301":"1250–1301","1263–1320":"1263–1320","1301":"1301","1311":"1311","1320":"1320","1331":"1331","1263":"1263","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","24 May 1280":"24. mai 1280","1270":"1270","about November 1311":"umbes november 1311","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Stainsby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"24 May 1280–about November 1311":"24. toukokuuta 1280–noin marraskuu 1311","1270–1331":"1270–1331","1280–1311":"1280–1311","1285–1331":"1285–1331","1311–Male":"1311–Kuollut","1250–1301":"1250–1301","1263–1320":"1263–1320","1301":"1301","1311":"1311","1320":"1320","1331":"1331","1263":"1263","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","24 May 1280":"24. toukokuuta 1280","1270":"1270","about November 1311":"noin marraskuu 1311","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Stainsby, Derbyshire, 